        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>1116 Walnut St.<lb/>
                May 28&#44; 1890.<lb/></p>
            <p>To Rev. Dr. Morais.<lb/>
                Dear Sir.<lb/></p>
            <p>My<lb/> sister&#45;in&#45;law&#44; Mrs.<lb/> J. Steering Tilge&#44; has<lb/> been interested lately&#44;<lb/> in a little child 18<lb/> months old&#44; who has<lb/> been ill and who has<lb/> been ill and who has<lb/> been an inmate of<lb/> the Mary J. Drexel<lb/> Home for some time.<lb/>  The child is of Jewish<lb/> parentage and my<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>friend&#44; Miss Mary<lb/> M. Cohen&#44; thinks you<lb/> are the proper person<lb/> to whom to apply to<lb/> find a suitable <del>per</del>&#45;<lb/> home for him.  He is<lb/> now pronounced well<lb/> and they can keep<lb/> him no longer at<lb/> the Home.  I forget<lb/> whether it is the father<lb/> or mother who is a He&#45;<lb/>brew.  The mother lives<lb/> out at services and<lb/> she says her husband<lb/> deserted her some<lb/> time ago.  Also<lb/> that she can pro&#45;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>duce her marriage&#45;<lb/>certificate.  Her ad&#45;<lb/>dress can be produc<lb/>ed at the Mary J. Drexel<lb/> Home&#44; on the German<lb/> Hospital grounds<lb/> opposite Girard Col&#45;<lb/>lege.  My sister&#45;in&#45;<lb/>law had found a home<lb/> for the child with a<lb/> German family&#44; who<lb/> afterwards decided<lb/> not to take him.<lb/>  I therefore take the<lb/> liberty of address&#45;<lb/>ing you.<lb/></p>
            <p>Very respectfully yours&#45;  &#40;over.&#41;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>Emma R. Tilge.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
